                        "id": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "value": "understanding-ptsd"
                        },
                        "thumbnail": {
                            "type": "image",
                            "value": {
                                "src": {
                                    "type": "string",
                                    "value": "assets/ptsd-awareness-month.png"
                                },
                                "alt": {
                                    "type": "string",
                                    "value": "PTSD Awareness Month graphic with teal and blue design"
                                }
                            }
                        },
                        "title": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "value": "Understanding PTSD: When the Past Still Feels Present"
                        },
                        "publishedDate": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "value": "June 2, 2026"
                        },
                        "body": {
                            "type": "richtext",
                            "value": "Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder, or PTSD, is a mental health condition that can happen after a person experiences or witnesses a traumatic event. This may include violence, accidents, abuse, disasters, war, sudden loss, or any experience that feels deeply frightening or life-threatening. PTSD is not a sign of weakness. It is the mind and body's response when trauma leaves a lasting impact.\n\nPeople with PTSD may feel like the danger is not fully over, even when they are already safe. They may experience flashbacks, nightmares, intense anxiety, unwanted memories, emotional numbness, irritability, guilt, or difficulty sleeping. Some people also avoid places, people, conversations, or situations that remind them of what happened. These symptoms can affect work, school, relationships, and daily life.\n\nPTSD can look different from person to person. Some may become quiet and withdrawn, while others may appear angry, restless, or always on alert. Children may show PTSD through behavior changes, play, drawings, fear, or blaming themselves for what happened. Symptoms may begin soon after the traumatic event, but for some people, they may appear months or even years later.\n\nThe good news is that PTSD can be treated. Support from mental health professionals, therapy, and in some cases medication, can help people process the trauma and regain a sense of safety and control. Talk therapy is one of the main treatments, and some medications may also help manage symptoms such as anxiety, sadness, sleep problems, or emotional numbness.\n\nHealing from PTSD does not mean forgetting what happened. It means learning how to live without the trauma controlling every thought, reaction, and decision. With the right support, patience, and care, recovery is possible. People with PTSD deserve understanding, not judgment. Sometimes, the bravest thing a person can do is ask for help and take the first step toward healing."
                        },
